402
00:32:47.390 --> 00:32:52.619
Mr. and Mrs. Kim threaten each other with
violence, though play it off as a joke. They

403
00:32:52.619 --> 00:32:57.279
take their newfound success for granted. And
they use the weekend to eat lots and drink

404
00:32:57.279 --> 00:33:01.600
expensive liquor without any regard to how
anything could go wrong.

405
00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:06.360
At which point the former maid, Moon-Gwang
shows up begging to be let in. She immediately

406
00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:10.739
goes to a secret basement hidden behind a
shelf in the pantry. As she was a maid who

407
00:33:10.739 --> 00:33:16.369
worked in the house from when it was originally
built, she has been keeping her husband there

408
00:33:16.369 --> 00:33:21.390
— the whole time in the basement — to
keep him away from loan sharks.

409
00:33:21.390 --> 00:33:27.649
Moon-Gwang literally begs on her knees for
Mrs. Kim, who succeeded her as the live-in

410
00:33:27.649 --> 00:33:32.830
housekeeper under a pseudonym, to not tell
anyone he is there, and to let her show up,

411
00:33:32.830 --> 00:33:36.570
now and then, to care for her husband. She
even offers a bribe. 

412
00:33:36.570 --> 00:33:42.129
At which point, Ms. Kim not only denies her,
but insults her, threatens to call the police

413
00:33:42.129 --> 00:33:47.429
— regardless of the fact that Ms. Kim and
her family, not long ago, were living in similar

414
00:33:47.429 --> 00:33:52.309
sort of desperation. Folding pizza boxes and
only getting paid for a fraction of the work.

415
00:33:52.309 --> 00:33:58.039
Ms. Kim had been portrayed as a bit of a b*tch
before then… but she was a likable figure.

416
00:33:58.039 --> 00:34:00.289
She was never this cold before.

417
00:34:00.289 --> 00:34:04.429
The other three Kims were eavesdropping at
the time, and accidentally slip and reveal

418
00:34:04.429 --> 00:34:09.020
themselves. Moon-Gwang and her husband record
the event on a phone, and threaten to reveal

419
00:34:09.020 --> 00:34:11.379
the whole plot to the Parks.

420
00:34:11.379 --> 00:34:16.419
And then the two families find themselves
upstairs. Moon-Gwang and her husband enjoy

421
00:34:16.419 --> 00:34:22.470
the merriment the Kims had afforded themselves,
while the Kims cower against the wall like

422
00:34:22.470 --> 00:34:26.790
hostages. Moon-Gwang and her husband rave
and recall the glory days of living in the

423
00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:31.799
open together, while exchanging compliments
about how powerful they are, waving around

424
00:34:31.799 --> 00:34:33.879
the phone they can blackmail the Kims with.

425
00:34:33.879 --> 00:34:39.190
A finger hovering over the ‘SEND’ button
compared to a North Korean dictator hovering

426
00:34:39.190 --> 00:34:40.849
over the ‘LAUNCH’ button.

427
00:34:40.849 --> 00:34:46.470
Moon-Gwang (before: so quiet, respectful,
and soft spoken) is now being compared to

428
00:34:46.470 --> 00:34:51.960
a dictator with a nuclear arsenal, and she
is revelling in it. But the Kims take advantage

429
00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:56.720
of the distraction, and wrestle the phone
from Moon-Gwang. In an extended full-family

430
00:34:56.720 --> 00:34:58.000
wrestling match.

431
00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:04.020
At which point it’s curious that these poor
people weren’t even fighting to be successful.

432
00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:10.079
They were fighting other poor people for who
will have the PRIVILEGE of licking the rich

433
00:35:10.079 --> 00:35:11.619
family’s boots.

434
00:35:11.619 --> 00:35:16.549
Just look at what Moon-Gwang’s husband had
been doing underground for the prior decade.

435
00:35:16.549 --> 00:35:22.119
He had… for some reason, taken to revering
Mr. Park so strongly that it approaches religious

436
00:35:22.119 --> 00:35:28.191
fanaticism. He concluded that the man who
owned the house over the bomb shelter he had

437
00:35:28.191 --> 00:35:31.980
spent so long in must be a man of great respect.

438
00:35:31.980 --> 00:35:37.670
Mr. Park arrives home every night at the exact
same time. Moon-Gwang’s husband is ready

439
00:35:37.670 --> 00:35:41.990
every night to activate the lights leading
up to the living room, and screams his praises

440
00:35:41.990 --> 00:35:46.619
to a Lord who cannot hear his reveries between
two meters of concrete. 

441
00:35:46.619 --> 00:35:50.260
Mr. Park does not know there is a man in the
basement who feels inclined to dedicate his

442
00:35:50.260 --> 00:35:54.760
every breath to him. And if he did know, he
probably wouldn’t be a fan of the idea.

443
00:35:54.760 --> 00:36:01.390
The point is that the rich are ambivalent
to the poor if they are not DIRECTLY serving

444
00:36:01.390 --> 00:36:05.750
or supporting them. And even then, they’re
disposable. Like the driver. Like the housekeeper.

445
00:36:05.750 --> 00:36:09.849
And the lights over the stairs leading to
the living room? The ones that Moon-Gwang’s

446
00:36:09.849 --> 00:36:15.390
husband ritualistically activates? The Parks
don’t think too much about it. Lights mysteriously

447
00:36:15.390 --> 00:36:19.279
turning on? It’s a rich people house. Don’t
worry about it. It’s a rich people house

448
00:36:19.279 --> 00:36:20.279
thing.

449
00:36:20.279 --> 00:36:21.279
It’s a sensor. 

450
00:36:21.279 --> 00:36:24.869
Later, when Moon-Gwang’s husband, his wife
now bleeding out after being pushed down the

451
00:36:24.869 --> 00:36:30.869
stairs by Mrs. Kim, bashes his bloody head
against the switch to tap out messages in

452
00:36:30.869 --> 00:36:34.539
morse code… it’s just the sensor acting
up. Pay it no mind.

453
00:36:34.539 --> 00:36:40.730
The literal life or death situations that
poor people are trying to communicate are

454
00:36:40.730 --> 00:36:48.859
dismissed as a malfunction. A glitch in the
system. Obscure messages needing to be decoded

455
00:36:48.859 --> 00:36:53.630
are just white noise. A byproduct of civilization.

456
00:36:53.630 --> 00:36:58.760
Ms. Kim accidentally-on-purpose murdered Moon-Gwang…
over who gets to have the ability to serve

457
00:36:58.760 --> 00:37:04.279
a made-up luxury beef ramen bowl to the Parks.
Complaining about how awful the rain is while

458
00:37:04.279 --> 00:37:06.670
a woman is dying under their feet.

459
00:37:06.670 --> 00:37:10.369
It’s worse than active hatred. It’s complete
ambivalence.

460
00:37:10.369 --> 00:37:16.720
Ms. Park praising the rain for clearing out
smog after the Kims have to take refuge from

461
00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:18.040
a flood.

462
00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:23.430
Mr. Park threatening to fire Mr. Kim if he
doesn’t don a ridiculous outfit to stage

463
00:37:23.430 --> 00:37:27.310
a ridiculous skit for a birthday party.

464
00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:32.720
And then Mr. Park’s complete disgust at
the sight of the Kim daughter’s blood. Refusing

465
00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:37.599
to call for an ambulance, instead demanding
Mr. Kim to give him his car keys so he can

466
00:37:37.599 --> 00:37:42.970
get away from the awful sight. Sheepishly
taking them for himself when Mr. Kim would

467
00:37:42.970 --> 00:37:45.339
not abandon his dying daughter.

468
00:37:45.339 --> 00:37:52.170
The final result is Ms. Kim and her son Ki-Woo
facing criminal charges, after the son endured

469
00:37:52.170 --> 00:37:58.980
severe head trauma. Tried, prosecuted, his
sister dead, and his father on the run. He

470
00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:01.569
has a brain injury where he laughs chronically.

471
00:38:01.569 --> 00:38:05.549
Why wouldn’t he? Smile. Things COULD be
worse.

472
00:38:05.549 --> 00:38:11.590
And Mr. Kim? He’s wanted for the murder
of Mr. Park. But it turns out that he’s

473
00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:16.799
been hiding in the secret bomb shelter. Living
as Moon-Gwang’s husband once did. Flicking

474
00:38:16.799 --> 00:38:22.720
on the lights for the new homeowners and sobbing
in grief to a magazine cutout of Mr. Park,

475
00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:28.530
who he regrets murdering, and misses dearly.
Reveres… even. 

476
00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:34.320
There is no change. No resolution. A couple
faces were swapped. Nothing gained; nothing

477
00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:35.869
lost.

478
00:38:35.869 --> 00:38:38.460
BUT! There is hope… 

479
00:38:38.460 --> 00:38:41.750
Nick: “For a better future?”

480
00:38:41.750 --> 00:38:43.069
PFFT. No.

481
00:38:43.069 --> 00:38:48.880
There’s hope that someday Ki-Woo will be
able to go back to school, be successful himself

482
00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:53.440
and one day buy that house so his father can
live in the light once more. But that’s

483
00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:59.530
just a dream. It’s just a hope. He has hope
that he will succeed in the system, so why

484
00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:00.829
does anything need to change?

485
00:39:00.829 --> 00:39:05.839
There… aren’t any heroes in this story.
This isn’t a story of how this one rich

486
00:39:05.839 --> 00:39:11.960
family was terrible. This was a story about
a social structure which permits this family

487
00:39:11.960 --> 00:39:20.569
to be this rich while these poor families
could be this poor. And how, at the end of

488
00:39:20.569 --> 00:39:25.480
it, the system only recognizes the rich people
as victims.

489
00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:29.920
The same set of laws which allowed the Parks
to be as wealthy as they were, were the set

490
00:39:29.920 --> 00:39:34.240
of laws which punished the Kims for doing
what they had to do the scrape by.

491
00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:39.980
Did the Kims get a bit too ambitious by replacing
the whole household staff? Did they bite off

492
00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:43.950
too much? Did they get too greedy? Maybe.

493
00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:50.760
But if petty drama to fire a few people is
greed… what does that make the Parks? Who

494
00:39:50.760 --> 00:39:55.350
have indicatively more than enough expendable
income to support all six poor people. Pay

495
00:39:55.350 --> 00:40:00.950
off their loans, pay for their wifi. Send
the Kim kids to school — it’s clear that

496
00:40:00.950 --> 00:40:03.990
they have the talent for it, but not the finances.

497
00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:08.600
In a system where you can be as talented,
motivated, and driven to pull off all the

498
00:40:08.600 --> 00:40:15.190
sh*t Kims managed to pull off — why do we
punish them for not having any options for

499
00:40:15.190 --> 00:40:19.580
how to use their talents?

500
00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:25.910
The film is called parasite because everyone
is one. The Kims, yes, leach off of the Parks.

501
00:40:25.910 --> 00:40:32.190
But the Parks have been leaching off of countless
families like the Kims. In class dynamics,

502
00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:34.420
parasites BEGET parasites.

503
00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:41.769
Which is worse? The ones who feed for their
survival? Or ones who feed for excess?

504
00:40:41.769 --> 00:40:44.809
The film’s answer is intended to be obvious.

505
00:40:44.809 --> 00:40:50.700
But, most unsettlingly, what does the film
suggest about the Kims’ son vowing to become

506
00:40:50.700 --> 00:40:55.619
successful enough to one day purchase the
house his father is trapped in? Does his goal

507
00:40:55.619 --> 00:41:00.289
make his quest for success any more noble
than why Mr. Park chose to be so wealthy? 

508
00:41:00.289 --> 00:41:05.450
We’ve seen how the Kims respond to privileges,
even imaginary ones. Who is the junior Kim

509
00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:10.460
going to have to become to fulfill his promise
to his father?

510
00:41:10.460 --> 00:41:17.480
By survival, the cycle continues. By success,
the cycle continues. Greed begets envy. Envy

511
00:41:17.480 --> 00:41:22.809
begets desperation. And that desperation begets
criminal labels on people who cannot succeed

512
00:41:22.809 --> 00:41:33.190
within the established system.

513
00:41:33.190 --> 00:41:38.819
What interests me is the fact that there are
so many parallel themes across Parasite and

514
00:41:38.819 --> 00:41:45.029
Painter of the Night. An Oscar winning film,
and an online comic. A modern day parable,

515
00:41:45.029 --> 00:41:49.740
and a historic erotica. Furthermore, that
a historic depiction of Feudal Korea contains

516
00:41:49.740 --> 00:41:54.119
the same structures of inescapable inequality
as a modern depiction of South Korea under

517
00:41:54.119 --> 00:41:55.440
capitalism.

518
00:41:55.440 --> 00:41:58.840
Because it’s not as if the circumstances
around wealth and privilege in Parasite AND

519
00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:04.730
Painter of the Night are just made up. For
many people, the Kim’s lives ARE a reality.

520
00:42:04.730 --> 00:42:09.661
There are plenty of desperate people willing
to do desperate things to survive, and even

521
00:42:09.661 --> 00:42:15.309
more desperate things to thrive. I grew up
with those people. A lot of things I had as

522
00:42:15.309 --> 00:42:17.710
a kid “fell off the back of a truck”.

523
00:42:17.710 --> 00:42:22.089
And Nakyum’s circumstances can be found
in a SHOCKING number of relationships. How

524
00:42:22.089 --> 00:42:26.410
many people stay with abusive partners because
they feel like they have no other option?

525
00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:31.280
That someone else might treat them worse.
The monster you don’t know is scarier than

526
00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:32.880
the monster you do know.

527
00:42:32.880 --> 00:42:39.690
And so it comes down to power. In Parasite,
the Kims have no power. In Painter of the

528
00:42:39.690 --> 00:42:45.960
Night, Nakyum has no power. And so they must
rely on people who do have power. And in our

529
00:42:45.960 --> 00:42:48.940
world, power and wealth are synonymous. 

530
00:42:48.940 --> 00:42:55.049
The queer community has forever been in the
shoes of Nakyum and the Kims. No power. Begging

531
00:42:55.049 --> 00:42:59.490
the powerful to let us have some scraps so
that we might survive. To make our relationships

532
00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:03.430
legitimate in the eyes of the law. To make
killing us a hate crime. To make our very

533
00:43:03.430 --> 00:43:06.450
existence legal.

534
00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:10.930
And those in power, mostly straight white
men, have the ability to make us do whatever

535
00:43:10.930 --> 00:43:17.099
they want in exchange for said scraps. Because
of desperation. The desperation of the powerless

536
00:43:17.099 --> 00:43:19.500
leads to disturbing things.

537
00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:24.619
The desperation of Nakyum to endure assault,
gaslighting, and rape in exchange for some

538
00:43:24.619 --> 00:43:29.329
amount of comfort. The desperation of the
Kims to throw other people in their social

539
00:43:29.329 --> 00:43:34.819
standing under the bus so that they can have
a vacation in a house that the owners of…

540
00:43:34.819 --> 00:43:40.230
take vacations from. The desperation of people
all over the world, fleeing wars, climate

541
00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:42.359
disasters, murderous governments, and fascism.

542
00:43:42.359 --> 00:43:46.690
I wanted to make this video because I read
an online comic with gay themes and thought

543
00:43:46.690 --> 00:43:49.970
I’d talk about it. Hell, with the third
season coming up, YouTube’s algorithm might

544
00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:51.820
even be nice to this video.

545
00:43:51.820 --> 00:43:56.480
But the more Nick and I dug into the subtext
of Painter of the Night, the more I realized

546
00:43:56.480 --> 00:44:02.029
that it’s not just a very well drawn porn.
On the surface, yes, absolutely. Porn. But

547
00:44:02.029 --> 00:44:06.930
under the surface, and not even that deep
down, there was a very intriguing commentary

548
00:44:06.930 --> 00:44:13.349
on class, society, and the desperate actions
of the powerless. The ongoing war of rich

549
00:44:13.349 --> 00:44:18.970
VS poor. Of the powerful vs the powerless.
Of the people who own things… and the people

550
00:44:18.970 --> 00:44:19.970
who own nothing.

551
00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:24.700
If you’re watching this video you’re very
likely a part of that second group. We’re

552
00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:30.089
all fighting back against a system set up
to keep us in a very specific place in society.

553
00:44:30.089 --> 00:44:34.940
With just enough hope to keep us going, but
not nearly enough opportunity for all of us

554
00:44:34.940 --> 00:44:39.329
to succeed. For all of us to reach the heights
of our potential.

555
00:44:39.329 --> 00:44:44.099
With the rich having their way, they’ll
have us attacking each other for scraps of

556
00:44:44.099 --> 00:44:48.170
opportunities. Hope has very limited vacancies.

557
00:44:48.170 --> 00:44:54.119
There is always a system, a Park Family, a
Seungho, keeping us in our place. Making sure

558
00:44:54.119 --> 00:44:58.370
we don’t reach too far, don’t ask for
too much. Not without their permission. Not

559
00:44:58.370 --> 00:45:02.880
without them controlling it, or at least owning
a piece of it. Telling us that we should be

560
00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:07.190
grateful that they give us the opportunity
to work for them, to create for them.

561
00:45:07.190 --> 00:45:13.180
The privileged get what they want. Whether
it’s tax breaks for hoarding wealth, a trip

562
00:45:13.180 --> 00:45:16.089
to space, or someone’s body.

563
00:45:16.089 --> 00:45:21.960
And, unsettlingly, it’s incredibly cost-effective
for rich people to just change the rules so

564
00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:26.640
they can get exactly what they want. If they
even feel the need. After all. If the punishment

565
00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:31.710
for a crime is just a fine, then that’s
a crime the rich can get away with.

566
00:45:31.710 --> 00:45:37.000
And isn’t that what we’re made to think
the entire purpose of wealth is? Being afforded

567
00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:42.329
opportunities to get what you want. No matter
what. The more you have, the more you can

568
00:45:42.329 --> 00:45:43.400
get away with.

569
00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:48.369
And it’s this pivotal association that I
think is so toxic. Wealth should buy comfort

570
00:45:48.369 --> 00:45:51.430
— not power. And certainly not survival.

571
00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:56.340
Our freedom — our agency is determined by
people who already have the freedom to do

572
00:45:56.340 --> 00:45:58.740
just about anything they want.

573
00:45:58.740 --> 00:46:06.079
As individuals, we may not have a lot of power.
But our strength is in Our cooperation. Our

574
00:46:06.079 --> 00:46:10.759
numbers. The rich know how powerful numbers
can be, and that’s why they do everything

575
00:46:10.759 --> 00:46:15.710
they can to divide us. To create as many minority
categories as possible. To pit the middle

576
00:46:15.710 --> 00:46:20.500
class against the poor. The poor against the
destitute.

577
00:46:20.500 --> 00:46:30.789
But if we could just, for a moment, show them
how powerful we can be together. There’s

578
00:46:30.789 --> 00:47:42.430
no telling the change we can bring.